column437:
comment:"Ordered around Friday and got delivered on Monday. Reasonably quick delivery. Have been running the unit for about 3 hours and i'm extremely happy with my purchase & following are the reasons why. 

I was initially skeptical that 0.75ton would be insufficient for my room which is larger than 10x10. 

I have a home office/study with a workstation (heavy desktop computer) and a laptop that generate some heat. 

Also im on the first floor where there is more heat.

Still the AC is running at turbo mode and the throw is similar to 1 ton. The build quality is very good and on par with other brands on market. The person who installed also said that dawlance ac's performance is very good. Go for pakistani brands rather than chinese brands. I hope the AC lasts some seasons since any new device runs best in its starting days. "}
column440: comment:"This is the only 0.75 ton air conditioner available in the market. Being an engineer myself
column441: I know that many rooms sized around 120 sqft in Pakistan requires only 0.75 ton AC. Now
column442:
there is an option and hopefully a good one in the long run.
Inverter air conditioners work best in Karachi if temperature is set at 27C or higher. I set it at 28C which is comfortable given the high ambient and the AC was sipping just 1.5A! This roughly translates to one unit of electricity in 3 hours. About Rs. 6 an hour. For an 8 hour daily usage I expect the bill to be about rs. 1500.

The AC is decent looking. Plastic is a bit flimsy on closer inspection but this is a non issue.

I just pray it survives at least three seasons. Like all local air conditioners
column443: I am afraid it will be the indoor which would develop leakage in the long run. Fingers crossed. "}
